# iOS Viewport And Safe-Area Rules

When fixing iPad or iOS layout clipping, black gaps, home-indicator space, or fixed bottom chrome, check the viewport unit model before changing padding or nav positioning.

## iPad / Tablet (`min-width: 768px`)

- For tablet+ app shells that must paint through the full iPad standalone viewport, prefer `100lvh` over `100dvh`.
- `100dvh` can stop above the iPad standalone safe/home-indicator region, leaving a visible black/dead area below floating UI.
- Keep this pattern consistent in full-height wrappers and table/list shells:
  - `src/app/globals.css`: tablet+ `html, body` use `100lvh`.
  - `src/components/ui/sidebar.tsx`: wrapper uses `md:h-[100lvh] md:max-h-[100lvh]`.
  - Section shells such as Business use `md:h-[100lvh]`.
  - Full-height table/list containers use `100lvh`.
- Do not compensate for an incorrect tablet viewport model with arbitrary bottom padding or negative nav offsets until `dvh` vs `lvh` has been checked.

## Mobile iOS (`max-width: 767px`)

- Preserve existing mobile behavior unless the task explicitly asks to change mobile.
- Do not globally switch phone layouts to `100lvh` without testing on iOS Safari and standalone PWA; browser chrome can make `lvh` hide content behind dynamic UI.
- Use `env(safe-area-inset-top)` and `env(safe-area-inset-bottom)` for fixed top/bottom controls and scroll padding.
- Do not add safe-area padding directly to `body`; it creates an unpainted strip above the app on iOS. Keep `body.has-device-safe-top { padding-top: 0; }` and offset actual chrome/components instead.
- Keep body scrolling disabled on mobile; sections provide their own scroll containers. Body scroll can create extra safe-area slack near the bottom nav.
- For phone shells that must paint behind the translucent iOS status bar, keep the app shell fixed to the viewport on mobile and avoid black PWA colors. The manifest/theme color should match the app page surface, not `#000000`.
- For scrollable mobile content behind fixed bottom navigation, keep bottom padding tied to the nav height plus safe area, for example `pb-[calc(max(env(safe-area-inset-bottom),0px)+80px)]`.
- If mobile shows bottom clipping or dead space, first verify the root shell height, body padding, safe-area variables, and service-worker/cache freshness before moving fixed nav elements.

### Mobile Black Status Strip Fix

If mobile content appears clipped by a black strip above the app, compare the normal app shell to an open Vaul drawer. Drawers paint as fixed viewport layers, so the status-area strip can disappear while the regular shell still exposes the PWA/body paint behind it.

Use this app-wide pattern:

- Keep `body.has-device-safe-top` at `padding-top: 0`; never bring back body safe-area padding to move content.
- Keep the mobile app shell fixed to the viewport, for example `max-md:!fixed max-md:!inset-0 max-md:!overflow-hidden` on the root shell wrapper.
- Set mobile/PWA paint colors to the app surface color, not black. Keep `theme-color`, manifest `theme_color`, and manifest `background_color` aligned with the page surface (currently `#24231f`).
- Move content down with section-level padding, not body padding. Use `pt-[calc(max(env(safe-area-inset-top),var(--device-safe-top,0px))+<existing-offset>)]` on scrollable section shells.
- Keep the top safe area painted by the app background; only the content should move down.

